Use Bayesian hypothesis weighting: assign prior probabilities to each hypothesis, then update them using likelihood ratios based on observed evidence. When evidence conflicts, treat each piece as a separate observation and compute the posterior probability for each hypothesis by multiplying likelihood ratios sequentially. Score hypotheses using Bayes factors—the ratio of likelihoods under each hypothesis—which naturally handles contradictory evidence by allowing some pieces to support different hypotheses. Assign weights inversely proportional to the uncertainty or reliability of each evidence piece if sources differ in credibility. For practical implementation: compute P(H|E) = P(E|H) × P(H) / P(E) for each hypothesis; the hypothesis with highest posterior probability is preferred. When evidence genuinely contradicts, this reveals model misspecification—investigate whether hypotheses are mutually exclusive or if hidden variables explain the conflict. Ensemble methods (averaging weighted predictions across all plausible hypotheses) often outperform selecting a single "winner" when uncertainty remains high. This approach quantifies confidence rather than forcing binary acceptance/rejection.
